What we need is a honking great system that can put hundreds of tons into orbit! I don't care how: laser launchers, transatmospheric vehicles, piggyback rockets, NERVA, whatever! How else could we put a 2001-type station into orbit? A thousand trips in a Space Shuttle? I've got this huge book detailing the development of the Shuttle system; it contains design studies of DOZENS of vehicles that COULD still be built, like those gargantuan Boeing SSTO's that were meant to put up O'Neils' solar power sattelites...<br>
Just think: some pointy headed physicist invents a faster-than-light propulsion system...so what! Perhaps we could build it, but then we couldn't put the damned thing up where it needs to be!  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uatomicredux.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AtomicRedux</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.geocities.com/marsmetaphysics/Cap0202.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/12/02 2:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=332.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/images/ezboard/user_images/Cap0202.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who else here thinks the X-Prize competition is worthles</span><hr size=1> The X-Prize is a good start I think, but not a giant leap. This is mostly due to strict regulations and the heavy bureaucratic environment of America that hampers incentives, innovation and experimentation. Just think if your rocket accidentally landed in Mexico and ruined some poor farmer’s corn crop, then you’d be @#%$ out of luck. Even though this would never happen to the careful private company that plans things out, the fact is that the folks in Washington would rather not have you escaping to Mars where you wouldn’t pay income taxes anymore. It’s better to have kids grow up and learn how to sue the Navy over killing a few whales.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/12/02 3:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=332.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who else here thinks the X-Prize competition is worthles</span><hr size=1> We have to walk before we can fly. We have to go suborbital before we go orbital.  The fact is that no private organization has ever constructed a reliable, reusable launch vehicle of ANY type, much less gone all the way to reliable, reusable SSTO.  I think the xprize is comparatively useless, but for different reasons.  The Xprize does not encourage the creation of completely reusable vehicles that could be used in a market context.  The vehicles will be 2-use vehicles that will go up, grab the prize, inspire a bunch of people, and never do anything ever again(most likely).  This is not the way to get people into outer space.  I'm working on an article that will cover most of this (highlighting, of course, my own biased view that XCOR Aerospace's way is the best).<br>
<br>
I think the X-Prize will capture public attention (has already in fact) and even if thats all it does, its worth it.   Most people have the mistaken view that anything that is capable of getting to outerspace or passing through outer space is heavy, expensive and dangerous.  The X-Prize competition will hopefully begin to change that view.  It will benefit private industry in that intangible woldview sense, at the very least. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 710<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/12/02 4:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=332.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Who else here thinks the X-Prize competition is worthles</span><hr size=1> And lets not forget that the X-prize winner may have a <br>
profitable vehicle for space tourism.<br>
<br>
With people paying $20 million for a week stay in orbit, <br>
how much would someone be willing to pay for a short <br>
suborbital flight of say 30 minutes of weighlessness?<br>
<br>
Not much you say?  How about we include a 'lady of the evening'<br>
for some zero-g enjoyment? Is low earth orbit the same as <br>
international waters as far as legalities?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Seriously though, once human space travel becomes reliable <br>
money maker, that's when space will open up for the rest of us. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 165<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/12/02 9:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=332.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: is the X-Prize competition worthless</span><hr size=1> The X-Prize is questionable. I also feel suspicion that it might not go anywhere after somebody wins it, but if it brings in a new era of cheap global 45 minute package/passenger travel, then maybe it will do the trick of getting people thinking of space as a place to do business.<br>
 The first thing is to use space to do business: travel through it. Next we'll get into using space itself as a business; space resources and environment.<br>
<br>
There's also a lot of difference between the X-prize and the new SLI (next Shuttle&quot; designs.<br>
One thing in common is that everybody seems to have abandoned SSTO -and about time, too. The push for SSTO held us back a decade or so. Was there anything worthwhile out of the X-33 diversion? Some materials sciences, maybe.<br>
<br>
 The new NASA space craft designs (the ones 'less capable &amp; smaller than Shuttle' are actually a good step. Maybe a private company could build &amp; operate something like Boeing's old SSPS lifter, but it's far more likely to be successful with something like the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/craft/hl20.htm">HL-20</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->/<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/craft/hl42.htm">42</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (or Grumman/orbital Science's SLI design spaceplane)<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>     <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a52.g.akamaitech.net/f/52/827/1d/www.space.com/images/h_grumman-orb_sli_eelv_02.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.space.com/missionlaunches/sli_firstphase_020430.html">Plans For Next Generation 'Shuttle' Ends First Phase; 15 Concepts Have Emerged</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
By Leonard David<br>
Senior Space Writer<br>
30 April 2002<br>
<br>
... One tough-to-do assignment for the SLI-derived launch system, (Dennis Smith, program manager of the SLI at NASA Marshall) said, is attaining a 1 in 10,000 probability of losing a crew. Today, the probability for crew loss onboard a shuttle is between 1 in 250 and 1 in 500, he said.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, a second-generation reusable launch system is being sought that lowers the cost-per-pound to orbit from $10,000 to just $1,000 a pound. The second-generation launcher would be capable of lofting crew and cargo separately.<br>
...<br>
<br>
One of the main goals of the SLI is a much safer and more reliable crew transport vehicle of some type, (Michael Coats, former astronaut) said. While the shuttle program has worked hard to make human space travel safe, it's 25-year-old technology, he said.<br>
<br>
&quot;We think we can do a whole lot better than that. So we're looking at an order of magnitude improvement in crew survivability,&quot; Coats said. &quot;To get closer to the 1 in 10,000 goal we need a crew escape system,&quot; he said. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yes, it's pretty pathetic that we're at this stage now. It does seem that the government (not just NASA) has artificially held back our space development, to ensure jobs for their ground crew.<br>
 Nevertheless, this new effort should maybe be supported, and urged to be done reliably (not the $5000 bolt, but responsibly costed).<br>
